<TITLE> UN peacekeeping chief arrives Wednesday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 06 (bdnews24.com)  UN peacekeeping chief Alain Le Roy arrives in Dhaka Wednesday on a two-day tour as a part of an official visit to troop contributing countries. Bangladesh is currently the second largest contributor of UN peacekeeping troops, out of 116 countries, with 9,849 military and police deployed overseas. A UN statement said Roy, UN under-secretary-general for peacekeeping operations, plans to meet with government officials and national authorities in appreciation of Bangladesh's contribution to global peacekeeping efforts. He is also scheduled for an open discussion on the current and future challenges of peacekeeping. The discussion will also refer to the effect growing expectations and increasing complexities are having on major contributing countries. "We know that the growing gap between demand for peacekeepers and the available supply complicates the contributor's task and increases the burden," Roy said in the statement. He also highlighted his intentions of this visit by saying "we are committed to seeking practical solutions to this rising challenge.
